The thing's rising up now and the crowd falls back.

03:54.360 --> 03:55.240
It seems plenty.

03:55.700 --> 03:57.520
Of course, it's a terrifying experience, ladies and gentlemen.

03:58.140 --> 03:58.920
They're fine words.

03:59.640 --> 04:01.140
Pull this microphone with me as they talk.

04:01.320 --> 04:04.020
I'll have to stop the description so I can take a new position.

04:04.160 --> 04:04.660
Hold on, will you please?

04:04.760 --> 04:05.400
I'll be right back in a minute.

04:05.400 --> 04:12.800
Of course, Wales started the tradition of the alien being both physically repulsive

04:12.800 --> 04:14.140
and hostile to human beings.

04:15.080 --> 04:20.520
And the pulp magazines picked it up through the late 20s and the early 30s into the 40s.

04:20.940 --> 04:25.080
The characteristic way of treating an alien was as a so-called bug-eyed monster.

04:25.600 --> 04:28.400
Then the movies picked it up and carried that on through the 50s.

04:28.500 --> 04:32.160
And meantime, the literature took a different trend.

04:34.900 --> 04:40.640
In the 30s, around 1934 Stanley Weinbaum published his story,

04:40.700 --> 04:42.920
which was one of the landmarks in science fiction literature.

04:43.920 --> 04:46.380
It was entitled, The Modern Martian Odyssey.

04:46.980 --> 04:51.980
And it was the first treatment in the modern period of aliens as sensitive creatures.

04:52.200 --> 04:57.940
Ones who were not hostile or aggressive, who had an environment and ecology of their own.

04:58.980 --> 05:00.760
It took place on Mars.

05:03.280 --> 05:06.900
And Weinbaum created three or four different types of aliens on the planet.

05:07.860 --> 05:11.860
And it's interesting for us to go back and read about those aliens

05:11.860 --> 05:14.260
because they were all based on the science of his day.

05:15.140 --> 05:16.900
For instance, one of them was a silicon creature.

05:17.660 --> 05:20.420
They figured Mars was made up of sand.

05:20.740 --> 05:25.940
So one of the aliens that Weinbaum developed for the planet was one who ate sand.

05:26.640 --> 05:28.240
This is quite possible.

05:28.480 --> 05:30.400
There are two kinds of chemicals that can support life.

05:30.620 --> 05:31.760
And carbon and silicon are the two.

05:31.900 --> 05:33.840
We're carbon based and silicon life is possible.

05:34.500 --> 05:38.840
And as Asimov pointed out with Weinbaum, he said he was the first one in the history of science fiction

05:39.940 --> 05:43.260
to develop an environment for an alien.

05:44.080 --> 05:49.180
Conceiving of him as having come from a non-earth environment as being part of an ecology, which was non-human.

05:49.780 --> 05:52.240
Having thought processes, which were non-human.

05:52.740 --> 05:55.280
Having a logical system, which was non-human.

05:56.300 --> 06:03.920
And Weinbaum, of course, also made one of his aliens anyhow a creature named Tweedle very friendly.

06:04.640 --> 06:09.400
A non-hostile, non-aggressive alien, which was very different from the bug-eyed monster tradition.

06:09.580 --> 06:10.580
And it went over very well.

06:11.500 --> 06:14.080
Weinbaum was in his late 20s when that story was published.

06:14.580 --> 06:18.700
And there was an immediate market and immediate imitators doing that kind of story.

06:18.700 --> 06:24.900
An alien who was non-aggressive, with whom contact could be established.

06:25.800 --> 06:28.480
And as I said, that was in 1934.

06:28.780 --> 06:31.740
And wonder stories when Weinbaum wrote that landmark story.

06:45.540 --> 06:48.180
There are several different kinds of first contact.

06:48.360 --> 06:50.700
We're going to be talking about most of them in this treatment.

06:51.000 --> 06:54.140
One of that being mankind's first encounter with alien beings.

06:54.940 --> 07:01.280
Are mankind and several other alien races coming in contact with a new alien race?

07:02.240 --> 07:06.020
Yeah, I think that has to be the criterion that no matter how many aliens have been contacted,

07:06.600 --> 07:11.080
there still is that special feeling about meeting up with a brand new alien culture.

07:11.220 --> 07:12.820
And the humans have to be involved with it, of course.

07:12.980 --> 07:19.600
No matter if they're along with other aliens or not, I think that has to be the main criterion of alien contact.

07:19.600 --> 07:29.880
Of course, the meeting up with the original first race is the most exciting and most important one.

07:30.440 --> 07:35.400
Because up until that time, the human race doesn't even know whether there are other races in existence, presumably.

07:35.920 --> 07:39.240
After one has been in existence, then the rest, you kind of assume, are going to be there.

07:40.240 --> 07:48.440
Usually, a first contact story will be very much tied to its particular culture or historical era.

07:48.440 --> 07:54.680
Today, for instance, we're very much tied up with more sophisticated approaches or more sophisticated environments for it,

07:54.680 --> 07:56.820
simply because we are expecting it to happen.

07:57.800 --> 08:03.120
But way back in the 30s and 40s, not long after the days of the bug-eyed monster motifs,

08:04.000 --> 08:08.200
many of the stories about first contact would be tied to what was happening in the world,

08:08.620 --> 08:11.940
for instance, wars, racial aggressions and so forth.

08:11.940 --> 08:15.900
After all, another race is alien.

08:18.580 --> 08:24.480
Xenophobia or hatred of strangers, for instance, can take place within the human race, not just with alien creatures.

08:25.640 --> 08:33.420
And probably one of the best first contact stories of all by Murray Leinster, entitled, Appropriately Enough First Contact.

08:35.940 --> 08:43.700
A spaceship meets up with another, well, a spaceship from Earth meets up with a spaceship from another culture,

08:43.820 --> 08:46.040
the first time that any kind of alien has ever been contacted.

08:47.020 --> 08:54.720
And one of the things that happens in the story before they actually meet the humans on their ship are discussing and worrying

08:54.720 --> 08:57.440
and wondering about what kinds of creatures are going to meet.

08:58.660 --> 09:01.980
And Leinster has one of the characters say this,

09:02.720 --> 09:04.340
what are we going to do about them?

09:04.880 --> 09:08.300
Maybe these creatures will be aesthetic marvels, nice and friendly and polite,

09:08.720 --> 09:12.220
and underneath with the sneaking brutal ferocity of a Japanese.

09:13.760 --> 09:20.500
Now you obviously know that was written during the middle 40s, during the Second World War, when the Japanese were our enemy.

09:21.340 --> 09:25.480
But you'll find that often to be a motif of the first contact story.

09:25.480 --> 09:28.040
But I remember that story did have a happy ending.

09:28.600 --> 09:36.200
They did, Leinster speculated that perhaps there would be friendliness between the two cultures.

09:36.300 --> 09:37.740
The way he did that was fairly clever though.

09:38.380 --> 09:43.160
Wasn't that the case in which the two different crews actually switched spaceships,

09:43.220 --> 09:46.740
so they went back to each other's planets in each other's spaceships,

09:47.040 --> 09:49.820
and avoided revealing too much about themselves that way?

09:50.300 --> 09:50.600
Yeah.

09:51.180 --> 09:53.960
That's one of the problems you'll meet in many first contact stories,

09:54.300 --> 09:57.140
that we don't want them to know where we are,

09:57.600 --> 10:00.700
and presumably they wouldn't want us to know where they are.

10:01.740 --> 10:05.380
And so one particular branch of the first contact story is when the two cultures,

10:05.520 --> 10:08.980
the humans and the aliens, meet somewhere in a neutral space.

10:10.060 --> 10:17.160
And the whole subject of that first contact story was the aliens and the humans were wondering how can we keep them from knowing where we come from.

10:19.840 --> 10:26.460
Another way an author might introduce a first contact story would be in the way that how Clement designed his story,

10:27.040 --> 10:28.700
The Needle, written in 1950.

10:30.580 --> 10:34.260
That being that it's a first contact story in reverse.

10:34.720 --> 10:38.180
It's the story of an alien making first contact with people on Earth.

10:39.340 --> 10:44.160
And the alien in this particular story is, his form is alien,

10:44.160 --> 10:49.600
but his feelings, his motives, his emotions are very much human.

10:50.100 --> 10:54.680
Therefore, that the reader is able to empathize with him and his plight.

10:55.440 --> 11:01.160
The alien is more or less a detective, and he is chasing a criminal.

11:02.240 --> 11:06.980
The alien's form is a small, gelatinous mass.

11:08.140 --> 11:13.060
And they work in a parasitic relationship with a host,

11:13.400 --> 11:15.580
and that's how the contact is made.

11:17.380 --> 11:22.680
The alien hero inhabits the body of a young man,

11:22.820 --> 11:29.240
and they, through various methods, are able to contact and communicate with each other,

11:29.620 --> 11:33.300
and then they go off in search of the criminal and eventually find and dispose of him.

11:35.620 --> 11:40.700
You think that's fair, you said that the alien was more or less had human feelings.

11:40.840 --> 11:43.080
You mentioned the fact that he was chasing a criminal.

11:44.880 --> 11:47.740
To me, a good first contact story, a good story about aliens,

11:47.860 --> 11:50.500
must have a credible alien.

11:51.340 --> 11:57.660
Surely some creature developing on another planet, another galaxy,

11:58.540 --> 12:02.260
would have a whole system of logic, a whole feelings if they had feelings at all,

12:02.260 --> 12:03.240
but were totally non-human.

12:03.460 --> 12:07.440
In fact, it would probably be very difficult to understand him from the basis of our psychology.

12:08.260 --> 12:13.980
The trouble is it's much easier for a writer to create, say, a bug-eyed monster,

12:14.060 --> 12:20.760
than to try and create an alien and his whole ecology and his whole society simultaneously

12:20.760 --> 12:23.620
and make it incredibly different from human society.

12:23.940 --> 12:25.160
It's a tough thing because we're all humans.

12:25.740 --> 12:32.220
The early presentation of the aliens, what we would call unsophisticated,

12:32.300 --> 12:33.420
I think they almost had to do that.

12:33.600 --> 12:39.960
An alien was usually something that looked weird, but felt like a human being.

12:40.720 --> 12:44.220
Quite often they emphasized physical or physiological characteristics.

12:44.640 --> 12:48.060
He's alien because he's got five arms and three heads and so forth,

12:48.240 --> 12:50.200
and they didn't consider things like his psychology.

12:50.820 --> 12:53.960
Later on, this became a little bit more evident.

12:53.960 --> 13:03.060
In fact, a lot of different parts of human culture were considered in the first context stories.

13:03.640 --> 13:07.640
For example, even religion, in the case of James Blish's case of conscience,

13:07.980 --> 13:12.440
in which an entire planet, according to what Blish is trying to make us believe,

13:12.820 --> 13:15.700
has been created by the adversary, by Satan,

13:16.180 --> 13:22.020
and the aliens on this, Reptilian, though they may be, are perfect creatures

13:22.020 --> 13:25.140
who have not evidently been involved in original sin.

13:25.580 --> 13:28.560
They're still living in essentially a garden of Eden sort of thing.

13:29.060 --> 13:33.360
And the reaction of the human protagonist to this is the focus of the novel.

13:33.720 --> 13:37.540
The aliens on the planet were Reptilian or like small dinosaurs.

13:38.800 --> 13:43.500
They were like a race of Vulcans, Mr. Spock, from Star Trek, and they used pure reason.

13:43.740 --> 13:46.620
That's one of the things that bothered the protagonist, the Jesuit priest,

13:46.620 --> 13:50.920
is that they had a perfect society, a perfect culture,

13:51.240 --> 13:57.840
yet they had no such thing as faith, no such thing as religion, in fact, no emotions.

13:58.220 --> 14:00.780
They went totally unreasoned and they had a perfect culture.

14:01.400 --> 14:05.640
And to the priest, that shook the very foundations of his faith,

14:06.000 --> 14:09.060
because to have religion, to have faith, you have to have faith.

14:09.380 --> 14:12.220
And these creatures did not know what that was.

14:12.960 --> 14:14.980
So it was a crisis of conscience for him.

14:16.040 --> 14:18.740
The ending of that novel, you might remember, was very ambiguous.

14:19.240 --> 14:22.040
I think Blish intended for that to be so.

14:22.520 --> 14:28.900
Yes. The planet was created out of an element, lithium, I believe, that was inherently unstable.

14:29.580 --> 14:35.120
And when an earthman landed on the planet or started to set up factories of certain kind

14:35.120 --> 14:41.620
on the planet to use this lithium, or either he caused the planet to disintegrate or to blow up,

14:41.620 --> 14:47.360
or the priest at the end of the novel exercises the planet and it disappears.

14:49.080 --> 14:54.840
And you are not told which actually was effective in the destruction of the alien race.

14:55.140 --> 14:58.800
Some readers might find that novel a little bit slow, but I think it's a fascinating treatment

14:58.800 --> 15:05.080
and probably more than, I would say, more than 90% of the first contact stories and novels that have been written.

15:05.160 --> 15:10.980
I think it's probably truer to some of the feelings that the human race will have

15:10.980 --> 15:13.320
when we actually do make first contact.

15:14.180 --> 15:19.380
I think one of the first problems the human race will have is, are these creatures created by God?

15:20.160 --> 15:21.040
Do they have souls?

15:21.880 --> 15:24.280
You know, given the fact they have intelligence, yet do they have souls?

15:24.780 --> 15:29.160
I think it's very easy here to see an analogy between the explorers of the old world,

15:29.260 --> 15:33.860
the Spanish particularly, when they came to the New World and discovered the Indian cultures.

15:33.860 --> 15:41.860
They had philosophical theological debates on whether these creatures, these Indians, had souls.

15:42.420 --> 15:46.360
You know, they could kill them and say, well, there's nothing wrong with this, they're animals, they don't have souls.

15:47.180 --> 15:49.700
I think we're going to have that problem when we do run across aliens.

15:50.460 --> 15:51.900
It's going to be a religious problem.

15:52.600 --> 16:01.160
And I think Blishe's book, A Case of Conscience, is probably the, well, is the classic treatment of that particular aspect of first contact.

16:02.960 --> 16:09.780
Another value or another insight that a first contact story can give people is to put a perspective on the human race.

16:11.280 --> 16:14.280
Of course, we think of ourselves usually as a center of the universe.

16:14.580 --> 16:20.420
We think of ourselves as being the most intelligent creatures, at least on this planet, if not in the universe, of the galaxy.

16:21.640 --> 16:24.940
And there are a number of first contact stories in which we learn humility.

16:26.160 --> 16:30.520
One of the best, I think, is Gordon R. Dixon's Dolphin's Way, published in the mid-60s.

16:30.520 --> 16:37.220
John Varley's universe, a good part of it, or the background of many of his books, comes from a similar idea.

16:37.980 --> 16:48.160
A group of a race of super powerful invading beings has taken over the earth and has decided to contact the most intelligent species,

16:48.420 --> 16:50.120
which in this case are dolphins and killer whales.

16:50.120 --> 17:00.660
In fact, we learn in one point in one of his novels that the invaders classify human intelligence, or classify terrestrial intelligences on three levels.

17:01.040 --> 17:03.740
There are the intelligent ones, which are dolphins and killer whales.

17:04.280 --> 17:17.640
There are hive minds, or levels in which groups of species can work together, like an ant colony or a termite colony.

17:17.640 --> 17:19.580
And he groups human beings along with these.

17:19.940 --> 17:23.260
Human beings are not intelligent individually, according to this classification.

17:23.660 --> 17:26.840
And on the third level are animals. And that's a very humiliating thing.

17:27.480 --> 17:34.660
The invaders wipe out civilization on the earth completely, human civilization anyway, without even stopping to worry about it.

17:34.860 --> 17:37.280
And they don't even contact human beings.

17:39.820 --> 17:49.100
Usually in most of these first contact stories, even if the contact is negative, that is the humans are made into an inferior race,

17:49.240 --> 17:53.920
or are shown as an inferior race compared to the aliens, at least there are some kind of communication possibilities.

17:55.000 --> 18:02.380
In truth, it might be the case that an alien would be so different from human beings, we wouldn't even be able to communicate with them.

18:02.480 --> 18:05.540
There are psychologists who would be so different that we'd have no common meeting ground.

18:05.540 --> 18:12.080
Or the technology on both sides, or the lack of it, maybe such that there would be no medium for communication.

18:12.200 --> 18:17.060
Yes, their technology may be so far ahead of ours that we don't even think the same as they do.

18:17.800 --> 18:22.940
I think one of the more interesting treatments in first contact would be Stanislaw Lim's Solaris,

18:23.160 --> 18:30.120
in that mankind has found a planet orbiting around a binary star system.

18:30.720 --> 18:38.840
But the planet's orbit is stable, which would be impossible, so they go to the planet to investigate why this planet's orbit is stable,

18:39.520 --> 18:48.400
and find out that the ocean on this planet, which comprises most of the planets set for a few islands, is a sentient or intelligent.

18:48.760 --> 18:55.460
So they set up stations and start trying to communicate with the planet, and therein lies the crux of the story.

18:56.700 --> 19:09.120
The hero, Chris Kelvin, has landed on a space station orbiting Solaris, and it has a few members of the crew left alive,

19:09.860 --> 19:11.820
a Dr. Snow and a Dr. Satorius.

19:13.240 --> 19:22.600
They both are, in essence, hiding out in certain parts of the ship and staying closed away from each other.

19:22.600 --> 19:29.660
And Kelvin has the responsibility or the obligation of finding out why all this is going on.

19:30.240 --> 19:38.700
During the early part of Kelvin's stay on the space station, his dead wife, Rhea, is materialized onboard the ship by the ocean Solaris.

19:40.460 --> 19:47.880
He is immediately horrified and finds a way to get rid of his first wife by sending her off in a ship.

19:48.460 --> 19:53.060
And about a day or two after that happens, his wife is rematerialized on the ship.

19:53.360 --> 19:57.900
This time her body is not composed of atoms and molecules.

19:58.060 --> 20:02.320
The way we know them is composed of neutrinos being extremely dense.

20:03.380 --> 20:11.440
But aside from that makeup of her form, she is totally human in every respect and is deeply in love with him.

20:11.440 --> 20:18.600
His wife had committed suicide previously because Kelvin had left her and she, in essence, died of loneliness.

20:20.240 --> 20:26.700
There ensues a type of morality play in which Kelvin tries to deduce why his wife is materialized at this particular time and space.

20:30.200 --> 20:38.180
And there's several levels to the story at this point in which Kelvin is trying to figure out why she got there, how she got there,

20:39.460 --> 20:42.380
why all this is happening at this particular point in time.

20:43.120 --> 20:59.880
And he finally deduces that it was the ocean which materialized his wife because his wife has knowledge which she would not have normally had had she been a living person and entity.

21:00.120 --> 21:07.080
She had knowledge of Kelvin's, some of his innermost thoughts which he had kept secret from his wife while she was alive.

21:08.560 --> 21:22.080
And in the end of the story, even though Kelvin can communicate with the creation of Solaris, he cannot communicate with Solaris itself.

21:22.380 --> 21:33.480
The concepts, the thought processes, our emotions, if there are any, of this being which is literally an ocean on this entire planet,

21:33.480 --> 21:41.140
are so far from that of human emotions, the thought processes, there can be no direct contact.

21:41.680 --> 21:48.640
And the enigma of Solaris at the beginning of the book is left the same at the end of the book.

21:49.060 --> 21:52.480
You'd probably call that a thought novel, wouldn't you? More or less on the...

21:53.380 --> 21:57.020
It's very much, I would call, psychological science fiction.

21:57.020 --> 22:05.400
But it's not so much the action, the typical hero or heroine, but the possibilities.

22:06.140 --> 22:09.140
Yeah, the psychological interplay between the two cultures and so forth.

22:12.640 --> 22:13.180
